stylometry:
The tradeoff is carrying costs and ordering costs and how much to order and when to order it. We need to order enough to support are demand always. Ordering a large amount of inventory will allow us to order less frequently. This will give us less ordering cost, but more carrying costs. In addition, what if the demand for that product suddenly drops. We just ordered a large amount of inventory that will take a long time to sell because of the decrease in demand leading to large carrying costs.
If we order small amount of inventory, we will have to order more frequently.  This will lead to less carrying costs but more ordering costs. In addition, if our demand exceeds our expectations between order points, than we have a possibility of a stock-out.
EOQ equalizes carrying costs and order costs by determining what amount of inventory is optimal during lead times.
